    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2636924518" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2636924518" />
    <a title="Ashma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27137459-ashma"><img alt="Ashma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590763122p2/27137459.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2636924518?book_show_action=true">May 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ashma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ashma" href="/user/show/27137459-ashma">Ashma</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143416333" href="/book/show/15849749-goat-days">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2636924518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12047692996382774757">Goat Days is a story of a migrant worker landing in the Gulf country from South Asia whose dreams are shattered by human-induced cruelty. &quot;Yes, I landed myself in prison because of my desire to live. Can you imagine how much suffering I must have endured to voluntarily choose imprisonment!&quot; Pg.12<br/><br/>When a &apos;merman&apos; Najeeb (merman because in South India, he literally works in water to collect sand for living) reaches the unforgiving Saudi desert, his Goat Days starts- the days of loneliness and slave</span>
  <span id="freeText12047692996382774757" style="display:none">Goat Days is a story of a migrant worker landing in the Gulf country from South Asia whose dreams are shattered by human-induced cruelty. "Yes, I landed myself in prison because of my desire to live. Can you imagine how much suffering I must have endured to voluntarily choose imprisonment!" Pg.12<br /><br />When a 'merman' Najeeb (merman because in South India, he literally works in water to collect sand for living) reaches the unforgiving Saudi desert, his Goat Days starts- the days of loneliness and slavery. His dreams of earning wealth for his family are buried somewhere in the sandstorm. This is the tale of an endless desert in Najeeb's life. Desert, though seem lifeless has the intriguing presence of life, an oasis, a hope. This book is Najeeb's journey towards the oasis. Where does his tale end? You need to read it to know it.<br /><br />This book emphasizes faith and hope. While reading pages where Najeeb yearns for shadow and appreciates even the shadow of his herding staff, I felt like I was drowning in the desert sand. While he is craving water and revisiting days where he took water for granted in his homeland, I couldn't push an ounce of water down my throat. His immense loneliness and solace with goats felt heart-aching. The translation is easy to read and gripping. While it keeps you excited to uncover the journey, at one point I felt the book is stretching unnecessarily. Nevertheless, Benyamin doesn't fail to pull the readers back by taking them to the wonders of the desert.<br /><br />Recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12047692996382774757" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

